arkshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Moffat, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Moffat, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Halliday","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: variant of   Holliday  . Halliday is also found in Ireland, where it is of English origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Holliday","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>halidai</i>, <i>holidai</i> ‘holy day, religious festival’ (Old English <i>hāligdæg</i>). As a personal name, it may have been given to one born on such a day, including Sunday. Compare   Christmas  ."]},{"name":"Hallada","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of Scottish and English   Halliday  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Moffat","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Moffatt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moffatt","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: habitational name from Moffatt in Dumfriesshire, a placename with uncertain etymology. This name has been established in Ireland since the 17th century, especially in the form   Moffett  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Katherine Halliday - Heiress of Moffat was born in 1350, in Moffat, Dumfriesshire, Scotland. She married Sir Wiliam De Somerville before 1370, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1428, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, at the age of 78, and was buried in Lanarkshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1350–1428":"1350–1428","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1370–1444":"1370–1444","1403":"1403","January 1370":"jaanuar 1370","1444":"1444","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","before 1370":"enne 1370","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Cowthally Castle, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, S